It seems the dev-bundle patched jar doesn't contain Arrow. The class might be in a different jar. Let me try to look at the class more directly - maybe Arrow is in the Paper API, not NMS. In 1.21.x, Arrow might be remapped. Let me just write the code and try to compile. If Arrow is not in the expected location, the compiler will tell me.

Let me take a different approach for Phase 4. Instead of spawning arrows manually, I'll use `releaseUsingItem()` which triggers the bow's native firing mechanism. This is the proper way to do it - the bow handles spawning the arrow internally.

For the wind charge, I'll use a similar approach:
1. Equip wind charge
2. Call `startUsingItem(OFF_HAND)` or `startUsingItem(MAIN_HAND)` depending on where the wind charge is
3. Call `releaseUsingItem()` to trigger the use

Wait actually, for wind charges, the item use is different. `WindChargeItem` extends `Item` and its `use()` method creates a `WindCharge` entity. The way to trigger this from code would be to call the item's `use()` method.

The cleanest way to "use" an item in NMS is:
```java
ItemStack stack = getItemInHand(hand);
InteractionResultHolder<ItemStack> result = stack.use(level, this, hand);
```

This calls `item.use(level, user, hand)` which is the same as right-clicking.

For the wind charge, `WindChargeItem.use()` creates a WindCharge projectile:
```java
public InteractionResultHolder<ItemStack> use(Level level, Player player, InteractionHand hand) {
    ItemStack itemStack = player.getItemInHand(hand);
    level.playSound(...);
    if (!level.isClientSide) {
        WindCharge windCharge = new WindCharge(level, player, player.position());
        windCharge.shootFromRotation(player, player.getXRot(), player.getYRot(), 0.0F, 1.5F, 1.0F);
        level.addFreshEntity(windCharge);
    }
    return InteractionResultHolder.consume(itemStack);
}
```

So calling `stack.use(level, this, hand)` should work for wind charges.

For self-propulsion with a wind charge, the bot needs to aim straight down (pitch = 90) and use the wind charge. The explosion will propel the bot upward.

